Individual electricity demand modelling: solution

  1. Load data and fit a basic Gaussian GAM:
library(mgcViz)
load(paste0(goodLocation, "/data/Ind_elect.rda")) # change this

fit1 <- bamV(load ~ dow + ID + s(instant) + s(temp) + s(day), data = indElec, 
             aViz = list(nsim = 50))

print(plot(fit1, allTerms = TRUE), pages = 1)

All effects seem important, according to the p-values.

  1. Now we use check2D to look at the mean residuals across two variables, we are looking for interactions between ID and some of the other covariates:
pl <- list()
pl[[1]] <- check2D(fit1, "ID", "instant") + l_gridCheck2D(bw = c(NA, 1))
pl[[2]] <- check2D(fit1, "ID", "temp") + l_gridCheck2D(bw = c(NA, 1))
pl[[3]] <- check2D(fit1, "ID", "day") + l_gridCheck2D(bw = c(NA, 5))

library(gridExtra)
grid.arrange(grobs = lapply(pl, "[[", "ggObj"), ncol = 2)

Here the mean residuals are normalized using simulations from the model. Hence values <-2 or >2 are important, and here we have some massive deviations from zero. Costumers 2 and 27 seems particularly difficult to forecast. Let’s look at the latter:

in27 <- which(indElec$ID == 27)
par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
plot(indElec$instant[in27], indElec$load[in27])
plot(indElec$temp[in27], indElec$load[in27])

Most of the consumption happens before 7 am, and at temperatures < 12 degrees. Maybe this is due to storage heating?

  1. Fit model with by-factor smooth for each costumer, but same smoothing parameter for each by-factor effect:
fit2 <- bamV(load ~ dow + ID + 
                    s(instant, by = ID, id = 1) + 
                    s(temp, by = ID, id = 2) + 
                    s(day, by = ID, id = 3), data = indElec, 
             aViz = list(nsim = 50), aGam = list(discrete = TRUE))

AIC is much lower, and the p-values reported by check are not significant now.

  1. We might consider including the effect of the lagged smoothed load:
check2D(fit3, indElec$load48SM, indElec$ID) + l_gridCheck2D(bw = c(NA, 0.1))

Smoothed load seems to be important, especially for households 2 and 18. We include a by-factor effect of smoothed load:

fit4 <- bamV(load ~ dow + ID + 
                    s(instant, by = ID, id = 1, k = 20) + 
                    s(temp, by = ID, id = 2) + 
                    s(day, by = ID, id = 3, k = 20) + 
                    s(load48SM, by = ID, id = 4), data = indElec, 
             aViz = list(nsim = 50), aGam = list(discrete = TRUE))

AIC(fit3, fit4)
##            df      AIC
## fit3 1097.546 8989.751
## fit4 1157.393 2661.545

Big improvement in AIC. We re-check the mean of the residuals:

check2D(fit4, indElec$load48SM, indElec$ID) + l_gridCheck2D()

Deviations are now in the range [-4,+4], still large, but better than before.

  1. Looking at some individual consumptions and predictions. Change the loop indexes to look at different costumers:
par(mfrow = c(3, 3), mar = c(2.1, 4.1, 1.1, 2.1))
for(ID in 1:9){
  ids <- which( indElec$ID == ID )
  subD <- indElec[ids, ]
  subP <- fit4$fitted.values[ids]
  
  kk <- 1:200
  plot(subD$load[kk])
  lines(subP[kk], col = 2)
}
